Do you know that 99% of our oranges today are imported from California? But do you also know that 150 years ago, during nearly half a century, it was California that imported its oranges from Tahiti? And this is just one of many examples that characterize this little-known American-Tahitian relationship. I'm writing a thesis on Americans in the 19th century at Tahiti and the islands of what is now French Polynesia. And often, history books about Polynesian tell us about the Franco-British rivalry over Tahiti, but forget the presence of Americans at the same time. Americans who were building, after all, the superpower they would be in the 20th century. And that's where I come in. I want to develop the idea of a Tahitian island that was once almost American, of this intense relationship between Americans and Polynesians, unrecognized by the French, which mainly remembers the force of British influence on this island. My research work on archival sources is bringing early results. The Yankees, as they were called back then, were numerous in the five archipelagos of what is now French Polynesia. And these islands were American before they were French. Not a U.S. colony, even though in 1813, Commodore David Porter annexes Nuku Hiva on his own initiative, without Washington's support. And you see here one of the few vintage images showing an American flag planted on Marquesan soil. But rather American influence and a strong impact before the French protectorate and annexation. Moreover, American whaling ships and other vessels were nearly ten times more numerous than those from other nations at Papeete port between 1830 and 1840. And it's there that you find the idea of an American colony. In 1854. In 1845, 19 whaling ships docked in Papeete. Among them, one French, one English, and all the others were... Americans. You can imagine then the economic impact, but especially social, of this presence. Furthermore, American evangelization in Tahiti and the islands resulted in the late 19th century in a deep-rooted foundation for three American-origin religions that have made some Polynesians to this day Mormons, Adventists, and Sanctifiers. My goal is therefore to make the 19th century known to Polynesian people, which is part of their recent past. In France, over 3,000 people are intoxicated by carbon monoxide every year, with over a hundred deaths resulting from these intoxications. Preventing this phenomenon is particularly complex because this gas is invisible, odorless, and tasteless. To establish effective treatments, it is also important to understand precisely how this seemingly harmless gas affects our organism. The first answer lies in our respiratory mechanism. Oxygen that we breathe is transported through the blood to a protein called myoglobin, which stores and redistributes oxygen to muscle tissues. And that's where our culprit gas intervenes. It seizes the place of oxygen at this protein, disrupting the supply of oxygen to muscles and our body can no longer sustain itself.

More precisely, carbon monoxide binds to an atom located at the center of the protein, which is represented in the visual accompanying me. You can see this protein as a complex labyrinth with the binding atom at its center. To study this phenomenon of binding more deeply, it is important to be able to simulate it, for example on a computer. To do this, we use mathematical models that will describe the interaction between the carbon monoxide molecule and the protein. We then realize that the structure of the protein and therefore the contours of this labyrinth change over time. As for the carbon monoxide molecule, once inside the labyrinth, it heads towards the center, i.e., the atom on which it will try to bind. And when it reaches a dead end, it simply waits for a change in the configuration of the labyrinth to find a new path.

Very well, you'll say. Only, these openings can take a very long time before appearing, typically after millions of iterations on our algorithm. During this time, the molecule remains blocked in the labyrinth and researchers get impatient in front of their computer. My thesis work consists in proving that there is a much faster way to simulate these appearances of path. I say that if my molecule stays enough time blocked in this labyrinth, it forgets all its past trajectory. I can then find a way to simulate future trajectories on several processors in parallel, which will allow me to significantly reduce the simulation time.

Beyond this public health issue, there are actually many other physical systems where these results could be used. Like how mathematics, no matter how abstract they may seem, can help us better understand the world we live in. Thank you.
